ere; representing pyruvate access from glyoxylate-containing networks follows the reported network logic (Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal direct pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation/hydrogenation yields alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The instruction set and literature summary both highlight hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from reduced carbon fixation chemistry on Fe-bearing minerals as a key prebiotic route feeding glutamate precursors (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface wet-dry condensation of glyoxylate and pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles; nitrogen sources can enhance yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-like C-C bond formation between glyoxylate and pyruvate followed by rearrangement/oxidation furnishes alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report identifies glyoxylate + pyruvate as a primary route to alpha-ketoglutarate in prebiotic networks, with yields enhanced by ammonia/amines under mild conditions and with relevance to reductive glyoxylate-cycle analogs (Muchowska et al., 2020; Wimmer et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface malonate-assisted synthesis of alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 5-6, wet-dry cycles, cyanide-enhanced reactivity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Malonate participates in condensation network with glyoxylate and pyruvate; cyanide increases carbonyl reactivity and promotes alpha-ketoglutarate formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report explicitly states that malonate combined with glyoxylate and pyruvate under pH 5-6, 50 degrees C, and wet-dry cycles yields alpha-ketoglutarate at 12-20%, with cyanide enhancing reactivity in reductive glyoxylate-cycle-like chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2020; Fares et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal hydroxy-ketoglutarate cycle step to alpha-hydroxyglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic redox-active hydrothermal setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction of the alpha-keto functionality affords alpha-hydroxyglutarate within an HKG-like cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies a hydroxy-ketoglutarate cycle and specifically notes alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid as a direct precursor/product related to alpha-ketoglutarate, supporting reversible redox connectivity between these compounds (Springsteen et al., 2018; Kitadai et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal dehydrogenation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal redox cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated oxidation/dehydrogenation of alpha-hydroxy acid restores the alpha-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report directly states that alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid can undergo dehydrogenation to form alpha-ketoglutarate, furnishing a distinct precursor route into glutamate chemistry (Kitadai et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker-like synthesis of glutamate aminonitrile from alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and TiO2-assisted surface chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, cyanide-rich pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia and cyanide convert the alpha-keto acid through imine/aminonitrile formation to a Strecker-type glutamate precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary supports abiotic conversion of alpha-keto acids to amino acids with cyanide and ammonia and identifies Strecker chemistry through aminonitrile intermediates as a route to glutamate and other amino acids (Miller, 1957; Commeyras et al., 2004; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of glutamate aminonitrile to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry hydrolytic cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the nitrile and imidate equivalents yields the alpha-amino dicarboxylic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly notes irreversible hydrolysis of aminonitriles as the step driving Strecker routes toward amino acid monomers including glutamate (Peltzer et al., 1984; Islam et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe/S-mediated reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"slightly basic pH 8.3-10.5, excess ammonia, inert atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia followed by mineral-mediated reduction to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically identifies reductive amination of alpha-keto acids such as alpha-ketoglutarate in the presence of FeS or Fe(OH)2 under aqueous slightly basic conditions with excess ammonia as a plausible prebiotic route to glutamate (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; He et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like formate-driven reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool, reducing conditions, formate as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia adds to the alpha-keto acid and formate provides reducing equivalents to yield glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research findings explicitly mention reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia to glutamate by formate as a proposed prebiotic route; while less experimentally resolved than FeS-mediated amination, it is literature-grounded and useful for connecting hydrothermal formate production to later pool chemistry (Weber, 1981; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with alanine to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or concentrated pool; reversible amino transfer analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino group transfer from alanine to alpha-ketoglutarate yields glutamate and regenerates pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies transamination as a biochemical assembly-like route from alpha-keto acids to amino acids, and the pyruvate/alanine pair is a natural coupled donor-acceptor set for alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate conversion in proto-metabolic contexts; this remains more analogical than direct enzyme-free consensus and is therefore moderately speculative but literature-consistent (Bada, 2013; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic mineral surface chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid imine formation with ammonia followed by reduction gives alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied framework explicitly includes reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on mineral surfaces in hydrothermal settings, and alanine is also reported among amino acids produced in Fe2+-catalyzed prebiotic networks (Keller et al., 2014; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal cyclization of glutamate to pyroglutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal dehydration/cyclization under anoxic hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular condensation of glutamate forms the lactam pyroglutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research findings explicitly mention hydrothermal transformation of glutamic acid to pyroglutamic acid as part of its environmental reaction network, indicating both synthesis and degradation interconnection (Kitadai et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal conversion of glutamate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"deamination/hydroxylation sequence under hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrothermal deamination/oxidation of glutamate regenerates the corresponding alpha-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary specifically notes that under hydrothermal conditions glutamic acid can be transformed to alpha-ketoglutaric acid by deamination or hydroxylation, showing bidirectional coupling between precursor and target (Kitadai et al., 2021).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate formed in protometabolic chemistry is directly aminated under Fe/S hydrothermal conditions to give glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-assisted hydrothermal-to-pool route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate generation feeds a later pool reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate plus ammonia to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker route from alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate is converted to a glutamate aminonitrile and then hydrolyzed to glutamate in surface pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glyconitrile to Strecker-glutamate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde and HCN form glyconitrile, which gives glyoxylate, then alpha-ketoglutarate, then glutamate aminonitrile and glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Malonate-cyanide surface condensation route\",\n      \"description\": \"A wet-dry malonate/glyoxylate/pyruvate/cyanide network yields alpha-ketoglutarate, which is then aminated hydrothermally to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydroxy-ketoglutarate cycle route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate enters an HKG-like redox loop through alpha-hydroxyglutarate before returning to alpha-ketoglutarate and being aminated to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Alanine transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is aminated hydrothermally to alanine; alpha-ketoglutarate produced elsewhere accepts the amino group in a biochemical-like transamination to form glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate plus surface glyoxylate convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Independent hydrothermal pyruvate and surface cyanide-derived glyoxylate converge at alpha-ketoglutarate, then proceed to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate-pyroglutamate hydrothermal loop\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate formed hydrothermally enters a reversible environmental sink as pyroglutamate, reflecting persistence and transformation in vents.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate-alpha-ketoglutarate recycling route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal glutamate interconverts with alpha-ketoglutarate, enabling repeated entry into direct amination, Strecker, or transamination branches.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glutamate", "overall_strategy": "This network targets glutamate through a literature-guided, cross-environment protometabolic scheme centered on alpha-ketoglutarate as the immediate precursor and on glyoxylate, pyruvate, and HCN as major hubs. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon feedstocks and Fe/S-mediated alpha-keto acid chemistry, including direct and indirect access to pyruvate, glyoxylate, alpha-ketoglutarate, and glutamate. Surface environments contribute cyanosulfidic and Strecker-style routes from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia to glyconitrile, aminonitriles, and hydrolyzed amino acids, while also enabling wet-dry malonate/glyoxylate/pyruvate condensation to alpha-ketoglutarate. Biochemical/prebiotic assembly-like steps then connect alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate by reductive amination, transamination, and formate-driven reduction. The 10 pathways are not 10 wholly unique terminal reactions, but 10 valid route sequences through one connected bipartite graph, with convergence at HCN, pyruvate, glyoxylate, and alpha-ketoglutarate.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2N2O", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glyconitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "methanoate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-