FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation to one-carbon reduced product.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-S minerals are reported to reduce CO2 to formate under vent-like conditions, providing reduced carbon for protometabolism and downstream alpha-keto acid chemistry; this is consistent with iron-sulfur world and vent CO2 reduction literature (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde from CO2-derived reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic subseafloor hydrothermal system, CO/CO2 hydrogenation context"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated carbon oxide hydrogenation generates small aldehydes as part of FTT-type product distribution.", "reasoning": "The literature summary identifies hydrothermal ammonia/formaldehyde chemistry and magnetite-catalyzed CO/CO2 hydrogenation as plausible sources of aldehydes relevant to prebiotic amino acid synthesis, including glutamate precursors (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cody et al., 2000)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface cyanosulfidic formation of glyconitrile", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and TiO2-assisted photochemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde gives cyanohydrin/glyconitrile und