ochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral interface or concentrated pool; reversible amino transfer analog"}, "mechanism": "Amino group transfer from alanine to alpha-ketoglutarate yields glutamate and regenerates pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The report identifies transamination as a biochemical assembly-like route from alpha-keto acids to amino acids, and the pyruvate/alanine pair is a natural coupled donor-acceptor set for alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate conversion in proto-metabolic contexts; this remains more analogical than direct enzyme-free consensus and is therefore moderately speculative but literature-consistent (Bada, 2013; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic mineral surface chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid imine formation with ammonia followed by reduction gives alanine.", "reasoning": "The supplied framework explicitly includes reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on mineral surfaces in hydrothermal settings, and alanine is also reported among amino acids produced in Fe2+-catalyzed prebiotic networks (Keller et al., 2014; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrothermal cyclization of glutamate to pyroglutamate", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-400K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal dehydration/cyclization under anoxic hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular c