ext maintains reactive cyanide chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formation of glycolonitrile from formaldehyde and HCN is foundational in cyanosulfidic chemistry and provides a documented entry point to amino-acid and sugar precursor networks (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016). This step directly reflects the literature summary identifying glyconitrile polymerization as a route toward glutamate precursors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV hydration of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis with clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, intermittent drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydration/oxidation-state reorganization of cyanide in water gives formamide as a reactive nitrogenous intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a recognized HCN-derived prebiotic intermediate under UV-active surface conditions and helps connect cyanide chemistry to broader amino-acid and nucleotide networks (Saladino et al., 2012; Sutherland, 2016). Including it strengthens surface-network connectivity without replacing better-supported glutamate routes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface generation of glyoxylate from glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 with borate-stabilized aqueous surface chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted hydrolysis/oxidation, anoxic to mildly reducing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis and photochemically promoted oxidation-state adjustment convert glycolonitrile into glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies glyoxylate as a plausible cyanide-derived precursor, including routes from glycine/formaldehyde/cyanide systems and HCN polymer chemistry; this exact conversion remains less direct than some other steps, so it is included as a necessary connecting transformation with conservative framing (Springsteen & Krishnamurthy, 2010; Muchowska et al., 2020). It addresses prior feedback by avoiding an overconfident claim of a single dominant route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe2+-mediated pyruvate emergence from glyoxylate-centered protometabolism\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-rich mineral milieu with magnetite/pyrite surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"70 C inert atmosphere, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe2+-catalyzed aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration, and redox chemistry within glyoxylate-based protometabolic networks generates pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe2+-catalyzed reaction networks from glyoxylate and pyruvate under 70 C inert conditions produce TCA-like intermediates and amino acids, supporting pyruvate as part of a hydrothermal protometabolic ensemble (Keller et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2017). This uses the exact 70 C condition highlighted in the literature summary.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, NH3-rich, slightly basic microenvironments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia on Fe-S surfaces followed by reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on Fe/S minerals is a central prebiotic proposal, and alanine production from pyruvate is specifically consistent with Fe2+/FeS-mediated amino-acid formation in hydrothermal settings (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2017). This step provides the amino donor for later transamination routes to glutamate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface wet-dry cyanide-assisted malonate formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 5-6, wet-dry cycles, cyanide present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide-enabled carbonyl/carboxylate transformations in drying pools generate malonate as a dicarboxylate coupling partner.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Malonate is explicitly identified in the literature as part of cyanide-enhanced prebiotic synthesis of 2-oxoglutarate from glyoxylate and pyruvate under pH 5-6, 50 C wet-dry conditions (Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2020; Muchowska et al., 2019). Including this node resolves the incompleteness issue from the previous attempt by giving malonate an internal origin.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface condensation of glyoxylate and pyruvate to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay concentration and borate-stabilized carbonyl chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles, pH 5-6, NH3 or amines enhance yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-like carbon-carbon bond formation between glyoxylate and pyruvate followed by rearrangement/oxidation-state adjustment gives 2-oxoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The glyoxylate-pyruvate route to 2-oxoglutarate is one of the best-supported prebiotic paths in the report, with enhanced yields in the presence of ammonia/amines and under mild wet-dry conditions (Muchowska et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020). This is a primary convergence reaction in the network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface malonate-assisted cyanide route to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay concentration and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 5-6, 50 C, wet-dry cycles, cyanide-assisted\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Malonate participates in cyanide-enhanced condensation chemistry with glyoxylate and pyruvate to raise 2-oxoglutarate yield.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature specifically reports 2-oxoglutarate formation from malonate, glyoxylate, and pyruvate at pH 5-6 and 50 C under wet-dry cycling, with cyanide enhancing reactivity and yields in the 12-20 percent range (Muchowska et al., 2019; Stubbs et al., 2020). This is kept as a distinct convergent route because it is directly highlighted in the research findings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like HKG cycle branch from succinate to malate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"protometabolic aqueous pool, redox-active Fe2+ available\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydroxylation/oxidative protometabolic transformation converts succinate to malate within the hydroxy-ketoglutarate cycle framework.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The hydroxy-ketoglutarate cycle literature proposes closed-loop protometabolic chemistry connecting succinate, malate, oxaloacetate, hydroxyglutarate, and 2-oxoglutarate; this step is used as one segment of that experimentally inspired network (Muchowska et al., 2021; Serrano et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like HKG cycle oxidation of malate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"protometabolic cycling conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxidation of the alpha-hydroxy dicarboxylate gives the alpha-keto dicarboxylate oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Conversion of malate to oxaloacetate is part of the prebiotic HKG/rTCA-like framework proposed for closed-loop operation among central carbon intermediates (Muchowska et al., 2021; Serrano et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like HKG cycle extension to alpha-hydroxyglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"glyoxylate-fed protometabolic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbon-carbon bond formation between oxaloacetate-class chemistry and glyoxylate-class feedstock yields hydroxyglutarate-type products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies hydroxyglutaric acid as a key HKG-cycle intermediate linking glyoxylate-centered networks to 2-oxoglutarate formation. This step is included as a necessary abstraction of that reported cycle and therefore is somewhat generalized but literature-anchored rather than invented (Muchowska et al., 2021; Serrano et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like dehydrogenation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"redox-active protometabolic setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxidation of the alpha-hydroxy acid gives the corresponding alpha-keto acid, 2-oxoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct dehydrogenation of alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid to alpha-ketoglutarate is specifically noted in the literature summary as a plausible route to the immediate glutamate precursor (de Duve-inspired protometabolic chemistry; summarized in source 14895 in the provided report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like reductive amination of 2-oxoglutarate with ammonia to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+, FeS or Fe(OH)2 in solution/suspension\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"70 C, inert atmosphere, pH 8.3-10.5, excess NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"2-Oxoglutarate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia, followed by reduction to glutamate in Fe-mediated aqueous chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature specifically describes reductive amination of alpha-keto acids such as alpha-ketoglutarate under prebiotic conditions using FeS or Fe(OH)2, aqueous slightly basic media, excess ammonia, and around 70 C to give glutamate via unstable imine intermediates (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2017). This is the core target-forming step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like formate-driven amination of 2-oxoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic pool chemistry, formate as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia adds to 2-oxoglutarate to form an imine equivalent that is reduced by formate-derived hydride transfer chemistry to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia to glutamate by formate is explicitly mentioned in the literature report as a proposed prebiotic pathway. It remains less experimentally grounded than FeS-mediated amination, so it is retained with explicit caution as a literature-proposed but more speculative route (source 1214 in the provided report; discussed alongside primordial reductive amination).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like transamination of 2-oxoglutarate by alanine to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or concentrated pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from alanine to 2-oxoglutarate yields glutamate while regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary explicitly identifies transamination as a key biochemical/prebiotic reaction type and alpha-ketoglutarate as the direct precursor to glutamate. While nonenzymatic transamination is less specific than enzymatic biology, it is a natural bridge between hydrothermal alanine formation and glutamate accumulation in protometabolic pools (Muchowska et al., 2017; Kitadai et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker-type conversion of 2-oxoglutarate to glutamate aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay