 \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents released as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis of CO2 reduction to formate is a core vent chemistry and provides a literature-consistent reduced C1 input for downstream reductive amination and cross-environment transport (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019 review context from source 995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic subseafloor/hydrothermal, reduced gases present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2/CO hydrogenation on iron oxide/metal surfaces yields reduced carbonyl products including methanal equivalents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is included conservatively as a reduced carbonyl source feeding the cyanosulfidic branch; literature supports hydrothermal CO/CO2 hydrogenation to reduced aldehydic products in Fe-bearing systems, though product distributions are mixed and this specific formaldehyde assignment is less direct than the formate step, so it should be treated as a necessary but lower-confidence connector (McCollom-type FTT context; source 2655/2656 overview; speculative connector noted).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanohydrin formation to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde gives glycolonitrile; minerals assist concentration and photochemical persistence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile is a key cyanosulfidic intermediate formed from formaldehyde and HCN under plausible surface conditions and is specifically identified in the research summary as an entry to amino-acid precursor chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; source 9376; source 21195/21196 context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface conversion of glycolonitrile to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV photochemistry followed by hydrolysis in wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation/hydrolysis of nitrile-derived intermediates yields glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The knowledge base specifically notes glyoxylate as a cyanide-derived precursor in prebiotic networks and from HCN polymer-related chemistry, though this exact glycolonitrile-to-glyoxylate conversion is less directly established than glycolonitrile formation; it is therefore included as a constrained connecting step with explicit uncertainty (source 23036; source 9376; speculative connector necessary for network closure).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe2+-protometabolic synthesis of pyruvate from glyoxylate-derived network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ in solution with iron minerals present\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"70 C, inert atmosphere, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe2+-driven aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration, redox and oxidative decarboxylation reactions interconvert glyoxylate-centered products to pyruvate within a protometabolic network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska and co-workers showed Fe2+-promoted interconversion among TCA/rTCA-like intermediates from glyoxylate and pyruvate at 70 C under an inert atmosphere, supporting pyruvate participation in the same protometabolic reaction set relevant to glutamate emergence (Muchowska et al., 2017/2019; source 9400).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"slightly basic to alkaline, anoxic, NH3 excess\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia on Fe-S surfaces followed by reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Prebiotic Fe-mediated reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is directly relevant to amino-acid formation and provides alanine for a transamination route to glutamate; the broader Fe2+-catalyzed amino-acid network includes alanine and glutamate from pyruvate/glyoxylate feedstocks (Muchowska et al., 2017/2019, source 9400; source 1025).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface wet-dry synthesis/concentration of malonate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles, mildly acidic to near-neutral pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentration and carboxylation/oxidation within glyoxylate-rich wet-dry systems produce malonate equivalents available for condensation chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature used malonate as an important participant in alpha-ketoglutarate-forming networks under wet-dry conditions, but its specific prebiotic source is less well constrained in the supplied findings; this step is therefore an explicitly speculative but necessary network-connection step to avoid leaving malonate orphaned (Stubbs et al.-type glyoxylate/malonate network context, source 6993/9401; speculative connector).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface wet-dry condensation of glyoxylate, pyruvate, and malonate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay/mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"50 C, pH 5-6, wet-dry cycles, cyanide present, ammonia or amines enhance yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/retro-Claisen and cyanide-assisted carbon-carbon bond-forming chemistry among glyoxylate, pyruvate, and malonate yields 2-oxoglutarate within a reductive glyoxylate-like network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is one of the strongest literature-supported convergence points: alpha-ketoglutarate forms from glyoxylate, pyruvate, and malonate under pH 5-6, 50 C, wet-dry conditions, with cyanide and ammonia/amines increasing yields to approximately 12-20% (Stubbs et al., 2020/2022; source 6993, 6983, 6944, 6981, 995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like HKG-cycle oxidation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable, 300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ redox-active milieu or mineral interface analog\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"protometabolic redox cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrogenation/oxidation of the alpha-hydroxy acid gives the corresponding alpha-keto acid, reinforcing the HKG cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature specifically identifies dehydrogenation of alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid as a direct route to alpha-ketoglutarate and discusses the HKG cycle as a plausible prebiotic loop (source 14895; source 10738; source 9399).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like reductive hydration sequence from fumarate to hydroxyglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous redox network\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"linked to HKG-cycle style protometabolism\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fumarate enters a protometabolic redox/hydration manifold that furnishes hydroxyglutarate equivalents in the HKG framework.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The HKG-cycle literature supports hydroxyglutarate-centered closed-loop prebiotic carbon chemistry, but the exact abiotic microsteps are less completely specified in the supplied summary; this reaction is included as a compact literature-guided module rather than a fully resolved elementary step (source 10738; source 9399; partially schematic).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like conversion of succinate to fumarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"redox-active mineral interface analog\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic protometabolic cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxidative dehydrogenation of succinate gives fumarate within rTCA/HKG-like networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Succinate and fumarate are reported members of the interconnected prebiotic TCA-like network derived from glyoxylate/pyruvate chemistry and thioester-linked protometabolism relevant to alpha-ketoglutarate production (Muchowska et al., 2019; source 995, 9400, 9401).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like production of succinate from glyoxylate-pyruvate protometabolism\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-compatible aqueous network\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, protometabolic carbon redistribution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol, redox, and decarboxylative network chemistry channels glyoxylate and pyruvate toward C4 dicarboxylates including succinate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Succinate is part of the Fe2+-catalyzed TCA-like network built from glyoxylate and pyruvate and links directly into alpha-ketoglutarate-centered protometabolism (Muchowska et al., 2017/2019; source 9400, 995, 9401).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like conversion of malate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"redox-active aqueous or mineral interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"protometabolic cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxidation of the alpha-hydroxy dicarboxylate furnishes the corresponding alpha-keto dicarboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Malate and oxaloacetate are explicitly noted among the prebiotic TCA/HKG-related intermediates tied to alpha-ketoglutarate formation and oxidative decarboxylation chemistry (source 10738; source 9400; source 9401).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like formation of malate from glyoxylate-pyruvate protometabolism\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-compatible aqueous network\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic protometabolic carbon chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-type carbon-carbon bond formation and hydration yield malate from lower-carbon oxoacids in a TCA-like network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Malate is one of the core products/intermediates of the Fe2+-driven protometabolic network seeded by glyoxylate and pyruvate and is relevant to downstream alpha-ketoglutarate access (Muchowska et al., 2017/2019; source 9400, 995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like oxidative decarboxylative branch from oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate manifold\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/redox-active protometabolic milieu\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HKG-cycle connected, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxaloacetate enters carbon-extension/redox chemistry furnishing alpha-ketoglutarate within hydroxy-ketoglutarate style protometabolic cycling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature explicitly connects oxaloacetate, malate, and hydroxyglutarate with alpha-ketoglutarate through the HKG cycle, although exact elementary abiotic steps remain incompletely resolved; this compact branch represents that literature-supported connectivity without inventing a modern enzymatic sequence (source 10738; source 9399; schematic but literature-guided).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker-type synthesis of succinic semialdehyde from glyoxylate-derived aldehyde chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted aldehyde chemistry in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylate-centered cyanide/carbonyl chemistry accesses semialdehyde intermediates that can feed Strecker-like glutamate precursor synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary specifically notes that glutamate Strecker synthesis is better justified via a semialdehyde precursor than by direct use of alpha-ketoglutarate. This reaction represents generation of such a semialdehyde intermediate from cyanide-enabled surface chemistry, though the exact prebiotic route is less directly established and is therefore flagged as a constrained speculative connector (source 2035, 6940, 6942; adapted to avoid the previously criticized direct alpha-ketoglutarate Strecker step).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker conversion of succinic semialdehyde to glutamate aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous pool, concentration by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Semialdehyde reacts with ammonia and cyanide via imine formation and cyanide addition to yield the corresponding aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the literature-backed Strecker logic for glutamate more faithfully than the rejected direct alpha-ketoglutarate Strecker variant: glutamate can arise from semialdehyde + NH3 + HCN through an aminonitrile intermediate (source 2035, 6940, 6942, 10835).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of glutamate aminonitrile to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry hydrolysis, prolonged aqueous exposure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration and amide hydrolysis yield the alpha-amino dicarboxylic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to alpha-amino acids is a core Strecker outcome and provides one of the clearest prebiotic routes to glutamate in the literature (source 6942, 22184, 2035).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like Fe2+/FeS reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS or Fe(OH)2 with dissolved Fe2+\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"70 C, inert atmosphere, pH 8.3-10.5, excess NH3 (>100 eq), anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia condenses with the alpha-keto acid to an imine/iminium intermediate that is reduced in an Fe-mediated aqueous environment to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the best-supported direct prebiotic-like route from alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate in the supplied literature: alpha-keto acid reductive amination under FeS/Fe(OH)2, slightly basic conditions, 70 C, excess ammonia (source 1025; also consistent with Fe2+-catalyzed glutamate formation in source 9400).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like formate-assisted reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none specified beyond prebiotic aqueous redox conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, formate-rich pool receiving hydrothermal input\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate serves as a reductant in conversion of the alpha-keto acid/ammonia adduct to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research findings explicitly identify reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia by formate as a proposed prebiotic glutamate route. This is less experimentally grounded than FeS-mediated reductive amination and is therefore retained as a literature-supported but weaker pathway (source 1214).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate by alanine to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none specified; mineral interface compatible\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from alanine to alpha-ketoglutarate gives glutamate while regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination is explicitly listed as a key prebiotic/biochemical assembly reaction in the instructions, and alanine is one of the Fe-mediated amino acids generated in the glyoxylate-pyruvate network. While less directly documented than reductive amination, it is a plausible bridge between alpha-keto acid and amino-acid pools in proto-metabolic systems (source 9400; source 995; included as a network-connecting prebiotic analog).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal cyclization of glutamate to pyroglutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal dehydration under hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular condensation/dehydration of glutamate forms the five-membered lactam pyroglutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal transformations of glutamic acid include cyclization to pyroglutamic acid, and inclusion of this branch reflects reported glutamate stability/interconversion behavior rather than a primary synthetic route (source 14913).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal deamination/oxidation of glutamate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-S mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal alteration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrothermal deamination/oxidation of the amino acid yields the corresponding alpha-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary explicitly notes hydrothermal deamination or hydroxylation of glutamic acid to alpha-ketoglutarate, supporting inclusion of a recycling loop between target and precursor (source 14913).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-mediated direct route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate formed in the glyoxylate/pyruvate/malonate surface network is transferred to a Fe-rich pool and undergoes FeS-mediated reductive amination to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-assisted alpha-ketoglutarate reduction\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate and surface-generated alpha-ketoglutarate converge in a mixed pool where formate reduces the alpha-ketoglutarate-ammonia adduct to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Alanine transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxylate enters hydrothermal Fe2+ protometabolism to pyruvate, pyruvate is aminated to alanine, and alanine transfers amino group to alpha-ketoglutarate to yield glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile to alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface glycolonitrile and glyoxylate formation, which then converge with pyruvate and malonate to alpha-ketoglutarate followed by Fe-mediated amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Semialdehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide chemistry generates a semialdehyde precursor, which undergoes Strecker conversion to glutamate aminonitrile and hydrolysis to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker route from reduced carbon\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon produces formaldehyde, then glycolonitrile and glyoxylate on the surface, followed by semialdehyde generation, Strecker aminonitrile formation, and hydrolysis to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinate-HKG reinforcement route\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxylate and pyruvate produce succinate in protometabolism, which progresses through fumarate and hydroxyglutarate to alpha-ketoglutarate and then glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Malate-oxaloacetate-HKG route\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxylate and pyruvate feed a malate/oxaloacetate branch of protometabolism that reaches alpha-ketoglutarate and then glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface alpha-ketoglutarate with formate completion\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface wet-dry chemistry forms alpha-ketoglutarate, while hydrothermal formate arrives independently; both converge to give glutamate in a formate-rich pool.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate recycling stabilization route\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate formed in any route can be hydrothermally deaminated back to alpha-ketoglutarate, which is then re-aminated, demonstrating a literature-supported precursor-target recycling channel that stabilizes glutamate access.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_023\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_022\", \"rxn_023\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glutamate", "overall_strategy": "This network centers prebiotic glutamate synthesis on the literature-supported immediate precursor 2-oxoglutarate (alpha-ketoglutarate), reached by multiple convergent routes from glyoxylate, pyruvate, malonate, and hydroxyglutarate across hydrothermal and surface settings. Hydrothermal Fe/S mineral chemistry supplies reduced C1/C2 feedstocks and pyruvate-like protometabolic intermediates; surface cyanosulfidic, Strecker, borate-stabilized sugar/aldehyde, and wet-dry chemistry generates glyoxylate, semialdehydes, and aminonitrile precursors; biochemical/prebiotic assembly then converts 2-oxoglutarate to glutamate by Fe2+/FeS-mediated reductive amination, formate-assisted reduction, or transamination. Ten target-reaching pathways are included, but speculative steps are minimized and flagged where direct evidence is weaker. The network also includes hydrothermal glutamate interconversion with pyroglutamate and 2-oxoglutarate to reflect reported stability/recycling behavior.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h2,4H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O4", "iupac_name": "propanedioic acid", "common_name": "malonic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O4/c4-2(5)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,4,5)(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H8O5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "pyroglutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-4-1-2-6-3(4)5(8)9/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "butanedioic acid", "common_name": "succinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H4O4", "iupac_name": "but-2-enedioic acid", "common_name": "fumaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxybutanedioic acid", "common_name": "malic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2,5H,1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-2-cyanopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamate aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C4H6O3", "iupac_name": "4-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "succinic semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents released as formate.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis of CO2 reduction to formate is a core vent chemistry and provides a literature-consistent reduced C1 input for downstream reductive amination and cross-environment transport (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019 review context from source 995)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde precursors", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic subseafloor/hydrothermal, reduced gases present"}, "mechanism": "CO2/CO hydrogenation on iron oxide/metal surfaces yields reduced carbonyl products including methanal equivalents.", "reasoning": "This step is included conservatively as a reduced carbonyl source feeding the cyanosulfidic branch; literature supports hydrothermal CO/CO2 hydrogenation to reduced aldehydic products in Fe-bearing systems, though product distributions are mixed and this specific formaldehyde assignment is less direct than the formate step, so it should be treated as a necessary but lower-confidence connector (McCollom-type FTT context; source 2655/2656 overview; speculative connector noted)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface cyanohydrin formation to glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde gives glycolonitrile; minerals assist concentration and photochemical persistence.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile is a key cyanosulfidic intermediate formed from formaldehyde and HCN under plausible surface conditions and is specifically identified in the research summary as an entry to amino-acid precursor chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; source 9376; source 21195/21196 context)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface conversion of glycolonitrile to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV photochemistry followed by hydrolysis in wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation/hydrolysis of nitrile-derived intermediates yields glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "The knowledge base specifically notes glyoxylate as a cyanide-derived precursor in prebiotic networks and from HCN polymer-related chemistry, though this exact glycolonitrile-to-glyoxylate conversion is less directly established than glycolonitrile formation; it is therefore included as a constrained connecting step with explicit uncertainty (source 23036; source 9376; speculative connector necessary for network closure)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe2+-protometabolic synthesis of pyruvate from glyoxylate-derived network", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "Fe2+ in solution with iron minerals present", "aqueous": "true", "other": "70 C, inert atmosphere, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Fe2+-driven aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration, redox and oxidative decarboxylation reactions interconvert glyoxylate-centered products to pyruvate within a protometabolic network.", "reasoning": "Muchowska and co-workers showed Fe2+-promoted interconversion among TCA/rTCA-like intermediates from glyoxylate and pyruvate at 70 C under an inert atmosphere, supporting pyruvate participation in the same protometabolic reaction set relevant to glutamate emergence (Muchowska et al., 2017/2019; source 9400)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "slightly basic to alkaline, anoxic, NH3 excess"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia on Fe-S surfaces followed by reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "Prebiotic Fe-mediated reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is directly relevant to amino-acid formation and provides alanine for a transamination route to glutamate; the broader Fe2+-catalyzed amino-acid network includes alanine and glutamate from pyruvate/glyoxylate feedstocks (Muchowska et al., 2017/2019, source 9400; source 1025)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface wet-dry synthesis/concentration of malonate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles, mildly acidic to near-neutral pools"}, "mechanism": "Concentration and carboxylation/oxidation within glyoxylate-rich wet-dry systems produce malonate equivalents available for condensation chemistry.", "reasoning": "The literature used malonate as an important participant in alpha-ketoglutarate-forming networks under wet-dry conditions, but its specific prebiotic source is less well constrained in the supplied findings; this step is therefore an explicitly speculative but necessary network-connection step to avoid leaving malonate orphaned (Stubbs et al.-type glyoxylate/malonate network context, source 6993/9401; speculative connector)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface wet-dry condensation of glyoxylate, pyruvate, and malonate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay/mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "50 C, pH 5-6, wet-dry cycles, cyanide present, ammonia or amines enhance yield"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/retro-Claisen and cyanide-assisted carbon-carbon bond-forming chemistry among glyoxylate, pyruvate, and malonate yields 2-oxoglutarate within a reductive glyoxylate-like network.", "reasoning": "This is one of the strongest literature-supported convergence points: alpha-ketoglutarate forms from glyoxylate, pyruvate, and malonate under pH 5-6, 50 C, wet-dry conditions, with cyanide and ammonia/amines increasing yields to approximately 12-20% (Stubbs et al., 2020/2022; source 6993, 6983, 6944, 6981, 995)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Biochemical-like HKG-cycle oxidation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, 300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+ redox-active milieu or mineral interface analog", "aqueous": "true", "other": "protometabolic redox cycling"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrogenation/oxidation of the alpha-hydroxy acid gives the corresponding alpha-keto acid, reinforcing the HKG cycle.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature specifically identifies dehydrogenation of alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid as a direct route to alpha-ketoglutarate and discusses the HKG cycle as a plausible prebiotic loop (source 14895; source 10738; source 9399)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Biochemical-like reductive hydration sequence from fumarate to hydroxyglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous redox network", "aqueous": "true", "other": "linked to HKG-cycle style protometabolism"}, "mechanism": "Fumarate enters a protometabolic redox/hydration manifold that furnishes hydroxyglutarate equivalents in the HKG framework.", "reasoning": "The HKG-cycle literature supports hydroxyglutarate-centered closed-loop prebiotic carbon chemistry, but the exact abiotic microsteps are less completely specified in the supplied summary; this reaction is included as a compact literature-guided module rather than a fully resolved elementary step (source 10738; source 9399; partially schematic)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Biochemical-like conversion of succinate to fumarate", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "redox-active mineral interface analog", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic protometabolic cycling"}, "mechanism": "Oxidative dehydrogenation of succinate gives fumarate within rTCA/HKG-like networks.", "reasoning": "Succinate and fumarate are reported members of the interconnected prebiotic TCA-like network derived from glyoxylate/pyruvate chemistry and thioester-linked protometabolism relevant to alpha-ketoglutarate production (Muchowska et al., 2019; source 9